ry()` and `makeTicketDetail()` fixtures to use `'BACKLOG'` as the default status. Update transition tests to test `BACKLOG → [READY, IN_PROGRESS, CANCELED]` instead of `TODO → [IN_PROGRESS, CANCELED]`. Add tests for the `READY` status. Update `DONE` terminal status test (unchanged). Update filter status options to include BACKLOG and READY.\\n\\n### 7. Ensure PlanHistoryView, TeamHistoryView, CarryForwardLineageView components are wired\\n- Verify these components (built in step 14 original) are importable from the Tickets route or accessible from My Week / Team Week pages as intended. If they are standalone components without route-level integration, add appropriate navigation hooks (e.g., plan history accessible from My Week page, team history from Team Week page, lineage from commit detail). This may involve adding sub-routes or tabs.\\n\\n**Component and integration tests:**\\n- All existing TicketsPage tests updated and passing with corrected status values.\\n- New test: BACKLOG and READY status badges render with correct styles.\\n- New test: status transition uses dedicated API method (not updateTicket).\\n- New test: filter bar shows all 6 status options.\\n- Verify PlanHistoryView, TeamHistoryView, CarryForwardLineageView test suites still pass.\\n- Verify typecheck passes (no stale type references to 'TODO').\",\n  \"requiredChecks\": [\n    \"lint\",\n    \"typecheck\",\n    \"unit\",\n    \"build\"\n  ]\n}\n\nYou are the first agent to work on this step.\nImplement the changes described above, run checks to verify, and fix any issues before handing off.\nBe thorough — the next agent will review your work and should find it correct.\n\nPrior observations from earlier steps (address if they fall within this step's scope):\n- [MEDIUM] step 1 backend/build.gradle.kts: Uses Eclipse JDT formatter instead of google-java-format because google-java-format (and palantirJavaFormat) rely on `com.sun.tools.javac.util.Log$DeferredDiagnosticHandler.getDiagnostics()` which was removed in JDK 25. Future steps should be aware of this constraint; a switch to google-java-format would require either downgrading the JDK to ≤24 or waiting for a google-java-format release that supports JDK 25.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/: Mockito's inline mock maker (InlineBytecodeGenerator) is incompatible with JDK 25. Switched to subclass mock maker via the extensions file. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests — not an issue for our service classes but worth noting for future steps.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/resources/mockito-extensions/org.mockito.plugins.MockMaker: Set to `mock-maker-subclass` to work around Mockito inline-mock-maker incompatibility with JDK 25. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests. Not an issue today, but future steps adding mocks of final types will need to handle this.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency is implemented for repeat calls, but the step also called for optimistic locking or compare-and-swap to protect concurrent runners. I did not see explicit concurrency protection beyond state checks.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency relies only on a state check (DRAFT guard). There is no database-level optimistic lock (`@Version`) to protect against concurrent auto-lock runners. This is acceptable for v1 given single-instance deployment, but a future step should add `@Version` to `WeeklyPlan` and a Flyway migration for the `version` column if concurrent scheduling ever becomes a concern.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ReconciliationService.java: The `getReconciliationView` method allows state RECONCILING or RECONCILED, but `setCommitOutcome` only allows RECONCILING. If a manager views a RECONCILED plan via `getReconciliationView`, then tries to `setCommitOutcome`, they get a 400. This is correct behavior but worth documenting clearly in the API.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ScopeChangeService.java: The `removePostLockCommit` method sets `outcome = CANCELED` immediately (pre-reconciliation). During `submitReconciliation`, this commit is treated as already having an outcome (CANCELED), which is correct. However, calling `setCommitOutcome` on an already-CANCELED (removed) commit during RECONCILING would allow overriding the post-lock cancellation — a guard could prevent this in a future step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: Peer visibility is filtered at the field level (PeerCommitView strips sensitive fields) but the \"current and next week only\" temporal constraint for peer callers is not enforced at the service layer — a peer can request any historical week. Not a breaking issue for v1 but worth tightening in a future step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: `checkCanAccessTeam` requires the caller to be a team member. An ADMIN-managed parent team manager without explicit membership in a child team would be blocked from viewing that child team's data. This is consistent with current behavior but the \"indirect reports' aggregates\" capability from the step spec is not fully exercised in the team-week endpoint.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: Peer visibility appears field-filtered, but the “current and next week only” peer time-window rule may not be enforced server-side for arbitrary requested weeks.\n- [MEDIUM] step 12 frontend/src/routes/MyWeek.tsx: The pre-lock validation panel derives soft warnings client-side from commit data, but the actual hard-error list only appears AFTER the lock attempt returns validation errors. This means the user sees the panel before errors are shown. A dedicated `GET /api/plans/{id}/validate` endpoint could provide server-side validation without actually locking, giving immediate feedback. This is a future enhancement.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/components/teamweek/ByRcdoSection.tsx: The ByRcdoSection only shows `totalPoints` (planned) per RCDO node since the backend's `RcdoRollupEntry` doesn't include achieved points. A future enhancement could add achieved point rollup to the backend DTO.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/routes/TeamWeek.tsx: The step calls for a manager team selector for users who can manage multiple teams, but the current host bridge only exposes `currentTeam` and the route param, not a selectable team list. The dashboard currently supports route-based team selection, but not an in-page selector.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/routes/TeamWeek.tsx: ByPersonSection supports `onViewMemberPlan`, but TeamWeek does not wire a click-through action yet, so the “view full plan detail for a direct report” behavior is still not exposed from the page.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/routes/TeamWeek.tsx: In-page team selector for managers with multiple teams is not implemented — only route-based selection via param. Step 13 spec calls for an explicit team selector widget.\n- [MEDIUM] step 13 frontend/src/routes/TeamWeek.tsx: ByPersonSection `onViewMemberPlan` prop is not wired to a click-through navigation action in TeamWeekPage, so the \"view full plan detail for a direct report\" behavior is not exposed.\n- [MEDIUM] step 14 frontend/src/routes/Tickets.tsx: The create-from-commit flow is accessible from MyWeek only (via CommitList). The Tickets page doesn't yet have a standalone \"create from commit\" action — the API endpoint `/api/tickets/from-commit` is defined but not directly used from the Tickets page. This is by design (the PRD says it's a commit action), but worth noting.\n- [MEDIUM] step 14 frontend/src/api/ticketApi.ts: `getPlanHistory`, `getCarryForwardLineage`, and `getTeamHistory` endpoints are defined in the frontend but have no corresponding backend controllers yet — they will return 404 until implemented in future steps.\n\nWhen done, explain what you reviewed, what you changed (if anything), and your assessment.\n\nEnd with:\nVerdict: approve  — if the step is complete and correct, no more changes needed\nVerdict: changes_made  — if you made fixes or improvements\nVerdict: replan_needed  — if the step is structurally impossible to complete as planned and needs controller-managed replanning"}],"timestamp":1774364742898}}
